7.1.10 - M365SR10: Absence of Data Loss Prevention (DLP) Policies
ISM controls:
•	Control: 1511; Revision: 2; Updated: Dec-22; Applicability: All; OS: All (Preventing unauthorised data exfiltration via cloud services)
•	Control: 0846; Revision: 6; Updated: Jun-21; Applicability: All; OS: All (Authorising and restricting access to data and applications)
•	Control: 1537; Revision: 1; Updated: Sep-22; Applicability: All; OS: All (Restricting user access to cloud service settings and data)
________________________________________
Current Risk
No Data Loss Prevention (DLP) policies are presently enforced to restrict sensitive information flow externally, reducing the confidentiality and integrity of sensitive agency information.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
ALMOST CERTAIN	x	MODERATE	=	HIGH
________________________________________
Recommendations:
1.	Deploy Purview DLP Baselines: Implement Microsoft Purview DLP policies across Exchange, SharePoint, OneDrive, and Teams, configured to detect and flag Australian Government sensitive info types (e.g., TFNs, Medicare numbers).
2.	Enforce 'Block' Actions on High-Confidence Matches: Configure DLP policies to automatically block the external sharing of files containing highly sensitive or protected information, rather than merely auditing the event.
3.	Integrate End-user Justification: Enable "Policy Tips" in M365 apps to educate users in real-time when they attempt to share sensitive data, allowing them to provide a business justification if an override is required.
- Treatment #1
•	Policy Identification: Identify and document the specific sensitive data schemas and classification levels used by the agency to inform DLP sensitive info types.
•	Staged Implementation: Roll out DLP policies in "Test Mode" (Audit) for a 30-day period to establish a baseline and tune out false positives before moving to "Enforce" mode.
•	Alerting and Incident Response: Configure the Microsoft Purview compliance portal to send high-priority alerts to the security operations team whenever a block action is triggered.
________________________________________
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
Establishing automated DLP controls significantly mitigates the risk of accidental or uneducated data leakage by staff. While a determined insider may attempt to circumvent these controls, the systematic blocking of known sensitive information types reduces the likelihood of successful exfiltration from "Almost Certain" to "Unlikely."
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
UNLIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	M

